			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I think it's lame, among other reasons, because it makes the meaning of the PRG-ROM size byte less correct. What if an emulator uses the number of banks to load the data from the file before looking at the mapper number? <br /></div><br />I have two answers for your comment.<br /><br />1) If the emulator uses the number of banks to load the data from the file before looking at the mapper number, 8kb PRG will never work on this emulator, because in iNes header there is no way to tell the size of bank. Only the emulators, that can check the mapper info and adjust mirror according to it, will be able to run it. This means: you get no working emulator, if you don't use a new mapper, but you will get some, if you USE the new mapper. <br /><br />2) Actually there is a way around this, though . If you use bank size of 1 for the 8kb rom, then the emulator will load 8kb PRG + the first 8kb portion of CHR rom to the PRG buffer. Then, you load CHR based on the bank information and check for the EOF has been reached presumptually.<br />If so, you can check for the mapper number and reload it with the proper mirroring, and it will work fine.<br /><br />Choose whatever solution you like, but in (1), you will get at least some emulators be able to run the rom only if you use a new mapper, while none if you don't. And in (2) these emulators will have no problem with the new mappered Galaxian. So both answer will beat you argument. <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's also lame because you are trying to fix something that isn't even a real problem to begin with (the game runs, what's the big deal?). There are several other problems with the iNES header that are far worse than this.<br /></div>
<br />
<br />The game is not running on the major NES emulator like Nestopia and fceux under iNes header, so it is a problem. 
<br />
<br />You may wanna say just use UNIF. But,  None of the major set you will encounter over the net will be using it. And I am pretty sure that nobody wants to waste their time to fix 3000+ iNES headered NES roms into UNIF headered ones. So it is not practical.
<br />
<br />Futhermore, assigning a new iNes mapper number doesn't have any effect on the board type declaration of UNIF header. If you don't like iNes header in the first place, why do you mind whether iNes mappers are being wasted or not? This will at least give iNes header users better compatibility.</div>

