				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">kshin981 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If the emulator uses the number of banks to load the data from the file before looking at the mapper number, 8kb PRG will never work on this emulator</div><br />As I understand it, the definition of an iNES header doesn't say "16384*nprg bytes unless mapper is X, Y, or Z"; it says "16384*nprg bytes" full stop.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And I am pretty sure that nobody wants to waste their time to fix 3000+ iNES headered NES roms into UNIF headered ones.</div><br />You wouldn't have to convert every ROM, just the ones that can't be represented as iNES.<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&#91;pino@laptop shooters&#93;$ ls<br />&#91;...&#93;<br />Galaga.nes<br />Galaxian.unf<br />Gradius.nes<br />Gun Nac.nes<br />&#91;...&#93;<br />&#91;pino@laptop shooters&#93;$ _</div><br />Besides, even if you want a 100% Pure UNIF collection, that's more the job of a ROM auditing tool similar to GoodNES: for each SHA1(PRG) and SHA1(CHR), it would store the correct UNIF chunks for this dump.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Futhermore, assigning a new iNes mapper number doesn't have any effect on the board type declaration of UNIF header. If you don't like iNes header in the first place, why do you mind whether iNes mappers are being wasted or not?</div>
<br />I mind whether iNES mappers are wasted because we need to save the mappers for boards used by actual games that we haven't dumped yet, such as new HKO games and new pirate multis.</div>

