						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">kshin981 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You wouldn't have to convert every ROM, just the ones that can't be represented as iNES.</div><br />Rom listers and collectors doesn't like that. It has to be either all NES or all UNIF. And I personally don't like using two standardized formats for one kind of system, either.</div><br />You may not like it, but it happens. GIF and JPEG, or PNG and JPEG, or PNG and ICO, etc.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Every rom auditing tool needs a DAT file to fix a collection. Somebody must manually edit 3000+ NES roms header and create UNIF headered collection before anybody can take advantage of these auditing tools</div><br />But my point is that a DAT file can be made once and distributed, unlike the ROM. And a properly run DAT project will take collaborative contributions, much like our wiki.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Again the total number of iNes mappers can be increased up to 2048 mappers if we are going to use the lower nibble of 7th byte of iNES header.</div>
<br /><a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/NES_2.0#The_proposed_solution" class="postlink">Actually 4096, per NES 2.0</a>. But even if there were four million possible mappers, there would still be a lot of resistance among emulator authors to making the bank size which currently "is defaulted to 16384 by the iNes author" depend on the mapper number, given that the status quo works for every commercial game on Famicom and NES save Galaxian. I'd like to see what kevtris, the principal author of the 2.0 revision, thinks of making PRG page size depend on the mapper number.</div>

