						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You may not like it, but it happens. GIF and JPEG, or PNG and JPEG, or PNG and ICO, etc.<br /></div><br />Not just me, it's a culture among the "rom" people (i.e. listers, collectors, etc... ). <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But my point is that a DAT file can be made once and distributed, unlike the ROM. And a properly run DAT project will take collaborative contributions, much like our wiki.<br /></div><br />OK. Open a wiki project, persuade emu authors and rom dumpers to joint the project, and make it going. I would say persuading Membler to open UNIF wiki project as a side project of nesdev is a good place to start. But until then, let's not talk about how a non-exisitng project can solve our problem. It is just a waste of time.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But even if there were four million possible mappers, there would still be a lot of resistance among emulator authors to making the bank size which currently "is defaulted to 16384 by the iNes author" depend on the mapper number, given that the status quo works for every commercial game on Famicom and NES save Galaxian. <br /></div><br />They may like it, you never know. <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'd like to see what kevtris, the principal author of the 2.0 revision, thinks of making PRG page size depend on the mapper number.<br /></div>
<br />I don't know who's kevtris, but the actual people that I would like to hear about this matters are the authors of Nestopia and FCEUX.  I think it is these two, who is curruntly leading the NES emulation scene. It will be likely that their solution, no matter what they do, will be a law.</div>

